fields.description:
Hi All,

In MANAGED-NOVLAN and MANAGED networking mode, one sets the VNET_DNS to the preferred DNS server IP address which would then be passed to the instances.

It is found that along with this a local loopback interface IP 127.0.0.1 is also set in the /etc/resolv.conf of the instance.

Ideally it is expected to have only what is set in VNET_DNS and anything else should not be there.

This is the CC configuration for VNET_* settings:

VNET_SUBNET="192.168.0.0"
VNET_NETMASK="255.255.0.0"
VNET_DNS="10.56.130.139"
VNET_ADDRSPERNET="64"
VNET_PUBLICIPS="10.68.122.2-10.68.122.248"
VNET_LOCALIP="0.0.0.0"
VNET_CLOUDIP="10.68.126.6"
VNET_MODE="MANAGED-NOVLAN"
VNET_DHCPUSER="dhcpd"

the 10.56.130.139 is a external DNS server.

but in our instance /etc/resolv.conf ,
nameserver 10.56.130.139
nameserver 10.68.126.6

Find below the dhcp configuration generated by the CC.

subnet 192.168.61.0 netmask 255.255.255.192 {
 option subnet-mask 255.255.255.192;
 option broadcast-address 192.168.61.63;
 option domain-name "eucalyptus";
 option domain-name-servers 10.68.123.247, 127.0.0.1;
 option routers 192.168.61.1;
}

Also it has been seen that the 2nd IP changes to the CLC IP automatically after sometime, 

subnet 192.168.61.0 netmask 255.255.255.192 {
 option subnet-mask 255.255.255.192;
 option broadcast-address 192.168.61.63;
 option domain-name "eucalyptus";
 option domain-name-servers 10.68.123.247, 10.68.127.6;
 option routers 192.168.61.1;
}


Please let me know if there are any additional questions.

comments.body:
interesting note. I swapped the dns ordering on the CLC's /etc/resolve.conf to

{code}
nameserver 8.8.4.4 
nameserver 10.1.1.254
{code}

and the resulting image ended up with:

{code}
[root@ip-172-17-119-236 ~]# cat /etc/resolv.conf 
; generated by /sbin/dhclient-script
search eucalyptus
nameserver 10.1.1.254
nameserver 127.0.0.1
{code}

I think the issue is where is the other IP coming from.  In the example you provided above, you had the additional nameserver value in the /etc/resolv.conf of the instance:

{code}
nameserver 10.101.1.15
{code}

How is this value set?  Is it set by the following cloud properties?:

{code}
PROPERTY	system.dns.nameserver
{code}

Thanks for looking into this.

Regards,

Harold Spencer, Jr.

The additional entry 

{code}

nameserver 10.101.1.15

{code}

Is the CLC itself. I am using a Cent OS image that runs dlclient which issues 
a DHCP requests to whomever replies :

{code}
(virtualdir)[root@b-15 ~]# euca-describe-properties | grep dns
PROPERTY	bootstrap.webservices.use_dns_delegation	false
PROPERTY	bootstrap.webservices.use_instance_dns	false
PROPERTY	system.dns.dnsdomain	localhost
PROPERTY	system.dns.nameserver	nshost.localhost
PROPERTY	system.dns.registrationid	04c62093-516e-4cf5-9ad3-accc343f0c26
}

{code}

which  localhost is in fact my CLC .

The euca_ns setting (127.0.0.1) is being received by the CC StartNetwork() , sent by the 
CLC in   StartNetworkCallback.java 

{noformat}


  msg.setNameserver( edu.ucsb.eucalyptus.cloud.entities.SystemConfiguration.getSystemConfiguration( ).getNameserverAddress( ) );


{noformat}


Setting VNET_CLOUDIP doesn't seem to affect it

Nor does setting 

euca-modify-property -p system.dns.nameserver=8.8.8.8

The initial value appears to be set on boot:

{noformat}

   if(sysConf.getNameserverAddress() == null) {
      sysConf.setNameserverAddress(DNSProperties.NS_IP);
    }
  
{noformat}
